<li id="cite_note-37"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-37">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFSantora2005" class="citation news cs1">Santora, Marc (January 17, 2005). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/17/obituaries/17flanagan_obit.html">"Dennis Flanagan, 85, Editor of Scientific American for 37 Years"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/The_New_York_Times" title="The New York Times">The New York Times</a></i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">April 1,</span> 2008</span>. <q>Dennis Flanagan, who as editor of <i>Scientific American</i> magazine helped foster science writing for the general reader, died at his home in Manhattan on Friday. He was 85. The cause of death was prostate cancer, according to his wife, Barbara Williams Flanagan. Mr. Flanagan, who worked at <i>Scientific American</i> for more than three decades beginning in 1947, teamed editors directly with working scientists, publishing pieces by leading figures like Albert Einstein, Linus Pauling and J. Robert Oppenheimer.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft.atitle=Dennis+Flanagan%2C+85%2C+Editor+of+Scientific+American+for+37+Years&amp;rft.date=2005-01-17&amp;rft.aulast=Santora&amp;rft.aufirst=Marc&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2005%2F01%2F17%2Fobituaries%2F17flanagan_obit.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AScientific+American" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
